  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Woman's Heart
  author: Lee Dal-choong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I gave you a lover's knot,
    yet you sent me a fan of reunion.
    Your heart, it seems, was never mine—
    your affections shift like clouds,
    a thousand times transformed.

    My joy remains unfinished,
    my face grows pale with endless longing,
    day and night I pine for you.
    I do not blame you for leaving me;
    your new love is so beautiful.

    But tell me—how long will beauty last?
    Time flies swift as arrows.
    Does she not know that even flowers fade,
    that beauty too must bow to age's touch?
  footnotes:
    - The 'lover's knot' (동심결) and 'fan of reunion' (합환선) are traditional symbols of affection and marital harmony in East Asian poetry, making their contrast poignant.
    - The poem employs a common classical theme of abandonment and the transience of beauty to suggest both the speaker's pain and a subtle vindication through time's inevitability.
